The way I think about conditional probability is this: look at the diagram, consider the events known to have occurred, and then _mentally block out everything except that._ Once we know the background fact(s), we're essentially dealing with a restricted world. Take the example of the known female winner. Once we know that event F in fact occurred, we can visually filter out David, and look at the F blob as though that were our entire world. In this restricted female-only view, the underage elements comprise a greater percentage of the total than they did before. And half of the rock-star elements have now been obscured, leaving only Kelly as the one-of-the-remaining-three. 
