null space of the coefficient matrix for the system of equations in Archetype I. 
 x = 
          3 0 - 5 - 6 0 0 1 
          
 y = 
          - 4 1 - 3 - 2 1 1 1 
          
 However, the vector 
 z = 
          1 0 0 0 0 0 2 
          
is not in the null space, since it is not a solution to the homogeneous system. For example, it fails to even make the first equation true. 4 
Here are two (prototypical) examples of the computation of the null space of a matrix. 
Example CNS1 Computing a null space, no. 1 Let us compute the null space of 
 A = 
 [ 2 - 1 7 - 3 - 8 1 0 2 4 9 2 2 - 2 - 1 8 
 ] 
which we write as N (A). Translating Definition NSM, we simply desire to solve the homogeneous system LS(A, 0 ). So we row-reduce the augmented matrix to obtain   
 1 0 2 0 1 0 0 1 - 3 0 4 0 0 0 0 1 2 0 
   
The variables (of the homogeneous system) x 3 and x 5 are free (since columns 1, 2 and 4 are pivot columns), so we arrange the equations represented by the matrix in reduced row-echelon form to 
 x 1 = - 2 x 3 - x 5 x 2 = 3x 3 - 4 x 5 x 4 = - 2 x 5 
 So we can write the infinite solution set as sets using column vectors, 
 N (A) = 
      
      
 - 2 x 3 - x 5 3 x 3 - 4 x 5 x 3 - 2 x 5 x 5 
      
